content.description: Start crouched with hands on the big flake-undercling and feet on the detached block below. Climb out the mini roof on nice ledges and top out.
content.location: The mini roof on the left side of the Death Star outcrop.

content.description: Start matched on the bulging flake with feet on the block below. Climb up and through a few sloping ledges to the top out.

The sit start to Death Star. SDS with left hand on a blocky undercling and right on an in-cut side-pull. Make an powerful move right to a blocky ledge before heading into the regular sequence of Death Star. Burly and sequential compression. All detached blocks are off for feet (even the very tempting belay ledge right where you want your feet to go).
content.location: Right side of the Death Star outcrop.

content.description:
A superb compression test-piece with incredible movement. Split grade is given for two variations

 Matt originally climbed the route by compressing the double arête feature with left hand on a blocky side-pull, right on a small triangle side-pull, and a knee bar.

 The other, slightly harder version starts matched on a blocky ledge on the right arête. Then climbs up a few feet before transitioning to the compression section and topping out. This way adds a few VERY high quality moves and makes the crux slightly harder, but less reachy. It's also more congruent with the sit start.
content.location: Right side of the Death Star outcrop.

content.description: An unusually featured, west facing outcrop.
